withThis.name: withThis
withThis.comment: Returns a dart-js.JsFunction that captures its 'this' binding and calls dart-js.JsFunction.JsFunction-withThis.f with the value of this passed as the first argument.

apply.name: apply
apply.comment: Invokes the JavaScript function with arguments dart-js.JsFunction.apply.args. If dart-js.JsFunction.apply.thisArg is supplied it is the value of this for the invocation.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides dart-js.JsFunction.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and dart-js.JsFunction.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the dart-js.JsFunction.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

[].comment:
Returns the value associated with dart-js.JsFunction.[].property from the proxied JavaScript object.

The type of dart-js.JsFunction.[].property must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

[]=.comment:
Sets the value associated with dart-js.JsFunction.[]=.property on the proxied JavaScript object.

The type of dart-js.JsFunction.[]=.property must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

callMethod.name: callMethod
callMethod.comment:
Calls dart-js.JsFunction.callMethod.method on the JavaScript object with the arguments dart-js.JsFunction.callMethod.args and returns the result.

The type of dart-js.JsFunction.callMethod.method must be either dart-core.String or dart-core.num.

deleteProperty.name: deleteProperty
deleteProperty.comment:
Removes dart-js.JsFunction.deleteProperty.property from the JavaScript object.

This is the equivalent of the delete operator in JavaScript.

hasProperty.name: hasProperty
hasProperty.comment:
Returns true if the JavaScript object contains the specified property either directly or though its prototype chain.

This is the equivalent of the in operator in JavaScript.

instanceof.name: instanceof
instanceof.comment:
Returns true if the JavaScript object has dart-js.JsFunction.instanceof.type in its prototype chain.

This is the equivalent of the instanceof operator in JavaScript.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
dart-js.JsFunction.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to dart-js.JsFunction.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If dart-js.JsFunction.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of dart-js.JsFunction.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns the result of the JavaScript objects toString method.
